# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: french-ironclad-invincible
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/antony-preston] Antony Preston was born in 1938 in Salford, Lancashire, son of the 16th Viscount Gormanston and Miss Julia O'Mahony.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/antony-preston] After becoming a wartime evacuee, he was educated in South Africa at King Edward VII School, Johannesburg, and the University of Witwatersrand.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/antony-preston] On his return to England he spent some years at the National Maritime Museum, Greenwich, before becoming Editor of the periodical *Defence*.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/antony-preston] During the 1970s he was employed by a specialist publisher, Conway Maritime Press, as editor of their *Warship* annual.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/antony-preston] He also produced the specialised newsletter *Navint*.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/antony-preston] In the early nineties, he took over as chief editor of the magazine *Naval Forces* at the German editorial group Mönch.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/antony-preston] He left to resume as editor of *Warships* in 1996.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/antony-preston] Antony Preston lived in London until his death in 2004.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/antony-preston] His son Matt Preston (born 1961 and the eldest of Preston's four children) has gained celebrity as a TV judge on *MasterChef Australia* and as a restaurant critic-columnist for the Melbourne Age & Herald-Sun newspapers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] A **frigate** (/ˈfrɪɡɪt/) is a type of warship.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In different eras, the roles and capabilities of ships classified as frigates have varied.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 17th to early 18th centuries the term "frigate" was loosely given to any full-rigged ship built for speed and manoeuvrability and intended for scouting, escort or patrol.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] By the second quarter of the 18th century, what is regarded as the "true frigate" was developed in France and subsequently copied by other navies.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] This type of vessel was characterised by a long sleek design with a single gun deck of 28 and 36 cannons, and an unarmed deck below used for berthing the crew.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In the mid-nineteenth century the definition of *frigate* was expanded to include the early ironclad warships, which also had a single gun deck.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] However, later developments in ironclad ships rendered the designation obsolete and the term fell out of favour in navies worldwide.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The term was reintroduced in the Second World War to describe a seagoing escort ship of intermediate size between a corvette and a destroyer.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] After the war, this definition has gradually expanded to include many different kinds of vessels, from large ocean-going anti-submarine warfare ships to corvettes, destroyers, and nuclear-powered guided-missile cruisers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The etymology of the word (Italian: *fregata*; Dutch: *fregat*; Spanish/Catalan/Portuguese/Sicilian: *fragata*; French: *frégate*; German: *Fregatte*) remains uncertain, although it may have originated as a corruption of *aphractus*, a Latin word for an open vessel with no lower deck.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] *Aphractus*, in turn, derived from the Ancient Greek phrase ἄφρακτος ναῦς (*aphraktos naus*) – "undefended ship".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The term *frigate* originated in the Mediterranean in the late 16th century, referring to a lighter galley-type warship with oars, sails and a light armament, built for speed and manoeuvrability.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The first recorded usage of the term seems to date from 1562, when Alonso Pérez, Duke of Medina Sidonia armed a galley fleet complemented with vessels called *fragatas* which were claimed to be invented by him.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] These frigates proved impractical and were retired soon.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Other sources state Medina Sidonia actually credited Álvaro de Bazán, Marquis of Santa Cruz with their invention.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The term was later used as an alternate name for the *galizabra*, a kind of galleass built by Álvaro's brother Alonso in 1584 as a cross between a galley and a zabra.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1583, during the Eighty Years' War of 1568–1648, Habsburg Spain recovered the southern Netherlands from the Protestant rebels.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] This soon resulted in the use of the occupied ports as bases for privateers, the "Dunkirkers", to attack the shipping of the Dutch and their allies.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] To achieve this the Dunkirkers developed small, manoeuvrable, sailing vessels that came to be referred to as frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In French, the term *frigate* gave rise to a verb – *frégater*, meaning 'to build long and low', and to an adjective, adding more confusion.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Even the huge English *Sovereign of the Seas* could be described as "a delicate frigate" by a contemporary after her upper decks were reduced in 1651.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The navy of the Dutch Republic became the first navy to build the larger ocean-going frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The Dutch navy had three principal tasks in the struggle against Spain: to protect Dutch merchant ships at sea, to blockade the ports of Spanish-held Flanders to damage trade and halt enemy privateering, and to fight the Spanish fleet and prevent troop landings.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The first two tasks required speed, shallowness of draft for the shallow waters around the Netherlands, and the ability to carry sufficient supplies to maintain a blockade.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The third task required heavy armament, sufficient to stand up to the Spanish fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The first of the larger battle-capable frigates were built around 1600 at Hoorn in Holland.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] By the later stages of the Eighty Years' War (1568–1648) the Dutch had switched entirely from the heavier ships still used by the English and Spanish to the lighter frigates, carrying around 40 guns and weighing around 300 tons.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 17th century, the term *fregat* in the Dutch Navy described any oceangoing warship carrying fewer than 40 guns.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The effectiveness of the Dutch frigates became most evident in the Battle of the Downs in 1639, encouraging most other navies, especially the English, to adopt similar designs.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The fleets built by the Commonwealth of England in the 1650s generally consisted of ships described as "frigates", the largest of which were two-decker "great frigates" of the third rate.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Carrying 60 guns, these vessels were as big and capable as "great ships" of the time; however, most other frigates at the time were used as "cruisers": independent fast ships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The term "frigate" implied a long hull-design, which relates directly to speed (see hull speed) and which also, in turn, helped the development of the broadside tactic in naval warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 17th century the term 'frigate' was sometimes applied very loosely and could be used for any warship.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] At this time, a further design evolved, reintroducing oars and resulting in galley frigates such as HMS *Charles Galley* of 1676, which was rated as a 32-gun fifth-rate but also had a bank of 40 oars set below the upper deck that could propel the ship in the absence of a favourable wind.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In Danish, the word "fregat" often applied to warships carrying as few as 16 guns, such as HMS *Falcon*, which the British classified as a sloop.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Under the rating system of the Royal Navy, by the middle of the 18th century, the term "frigate" was technically restricted to single-decked ships of the fifth rate, though small 28-gun frigates were classed as sixth rate.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The classic sailing frigate, or "true frigate", well-known today for its role in the Napoleonic Wars, can be traced back to French developments in the second quarter of the 18th century.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The French-built *Médée* of 1740 is often regarded as the first example of this type.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] These ships were square-rigged and carried all their main guns on a single continuous upper deck.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The lower deck, known as the "gun deck", now carried no armament, and functioned as a "berth deck" where the crew lived, and was in fact placed below the waterline of the new frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The typical earlier cruiser had a partially armed lower deck, from which it was known as a "half-battery" or *demi-batterie* ship.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Removing the guns from this deck allowed the height of the hull upperworks to be lowered, giving the resulting "true-frigate" much improved sailing qualities.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy captured a number of the new French frigates, including *Médée*, during the War of the Austrian Succession (1740–1748) and the British were impressed by them, particularly for their inshore handling capabilities.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] They soon built copies (ordered in 1747), based on a French privateer named *Tygre*, and started to adapt the type to their own needs, setting the standard for other frigates as the leading naval power.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] However, most ships of this size were called "ship sloops".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] A total of fifty-nine French sailing frigates were built between 1777 and 1790, with a standard design averaging a hull length of 135 ft (41 m) and an average draught of 13 ft (4.0 m).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The new frigates recorded sailing speeds of up to 14 knots (26 km/h; 16 mph), significantly faster than their predecessor vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1778, the British Admiralty introduced a larger "heavy" frigate, with a main battery of twenty-six or twenty-eight 18-pounder guns (with smaller guns carried on the quarterdeck and forecastle).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] This move may reflect the naval conditions at the time; with both France and Spain as enemies, the usual British preponderance in ship numbers was no longer the case and there was pressure on the British to produce cruisers of individually greater force.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In reply, the first French 18-pounder frigates were laid down in 1781.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The 18-pounder frigate eventually became the standard frigate of the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The British produced larger, 38-gun, and slightly smaller, 36-gun, versions and also a 32-gun design that can be considered an 'economy version'.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The 32-gun frigates also had the advantage that they could be built by the many smaller, less-specialised shipbuilders.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates could (and usually did) additionally carry smaller carriage-mounted guns on their quarterdecks and forecastles (the superstructures above the upper deck).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1778 the Carron Iron Company of Scotland produced a naval gun which would revolutionise the armament of smaller naval vessels, including the frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The carronade was a large calibre, short-barrelled naval cannon which was light, quick to reload and needed a smaller crew than a conventional long gun.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Due to its lightness it could be mounted on the forecastle and quarterdeck of frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] It greatly increased the firepower, measured in weight of metal (the combined weight of all projectiles fired in one broadside), of these vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The disadvantages of the carronade were that it had a much shorter range and was less accurate than a long gun.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The British quickly saw the advantages of the new weapon and soon employed it on a wide scale.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The US Navy also copied the design soon after its appearance.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The French and other nations eventually adopted variations of the weapon in succeeding decades.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The typical heavy frigate had a main armament of 18-pounder long guns, plus 32-pounder carronades mounted on its upper decks.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The first "super-heavy frigates", armed with 24-pounder long guns, were built by the naval architect F H Chapman for the Swedish navy in 1782.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Because of a shortage of ships-of-the-line, the Swedes wanted these frigates, the *Bellona* class, to be able to stand in the battle line in an emergency.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] It is not known whether the French were seeking to produce very potent cruisers or merely to address stability problems in old ships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The British, alarmed by the prospect of these powerful heavy frigates, responded by rasée-ing three of their smaller 64-gun battleships, including *Indefatigable*, which went on to have a very successful career as a frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] At this time the British also built a few 24-pounder-armed large frigates, the most successful of which was HMS *Endymion* (1,277 tons).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1797, three of the United States Navy's first six major ships were rated as 44-gun frigates, which operationally carried fifty-six to sixty 24-pounder long guns and 32-pounder or 42-pounder carronades on two decks; they were exceptionally powerful.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] USS *Constitution*, preserved as a museum ship by the US Navy, is the oldest commissioned warship afloat, and is a surviving example of a frigate from the Age of Sail.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] *Constitution* and her sister ships *President* and *United States* were created in a response to deal with the Barbary Coast pirates and in conjunction with the Naval Act of 1794.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Joshua Humphreys proposed that only live oak, a tree that grew only in America, should be used to build these ships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The Admiralty, concerned by repeated defeats in single-ship actions, responded to the success of the American 44s in three ways.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] They built a class of conventional 40-gun, 24-pounder armed frigates on the lines of *Endymion*.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] They cut down three old 74-gun Ships-of-the-Line into *rasées*, producing frigates with a 32-pounder main armament, supplemented by 42-pounder carronades.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] These had an armament that far exceeded the power of the American ships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Finally, *Leander* and *Newcastle*, 1,500-ton spar-decked frigates (with an enclosed waist, giving a continuous line of guns from bow to stern at the level of the quarterdeck/forecastle), were built, which were an almost exact match in size and firepower to the American 44-gun frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates were perhaps the hardest-worked of warship types during the Age of Sail.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] While smaller than a ship-of-the-line, they were formidable opponents for the large numbers of sloops and gunboats, not to mention privateers or merchantmen.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Able to carry six months' stores, they had very long range; and vessels larger than frigates were considered too valuable to operate independently.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates scouted for the fleet, went on commerce-raiding missions and patrols, and conveyed messages and dignitaries.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Usually, frigates would fight in small numbers or singly against other frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] They would avoid contact with ships-of-the-line; even in the midst of a fleet engagement it was bad etiquette for a ship of the line to fire on an enemy frigate which had not fired first.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates were involved in fleet battles, often as "repeating frigates".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In the smoke and confusion of battle, signals made by the fleet commander, whose flagship might be in the thick of the fighting, might be missed by the other ships of the fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates were therefore stationed to windward or leeward of the main line of battle, and had to maintain a clear line of sight to the commander's flagship.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Signals from the flagship were then repeated by the frigates, which themselves standing out of the line and clear from the smoke and disorder of battle, could be more easily seen by the other ships of the fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] If damage or loss of masts prevented the flagship from making clear conventional signals, the repeating frigates could interpret them and hoist their own in the correct manner, passing on the commander's instructions clearly.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] For officers in the Royal Navy, a frigate was a desirable posting.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates often saw action, which meant a greater chance of glory, promotion, and prize money.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Unlike larger ships that were placed in ordinary, frigates were kept in service in peacetime as a cost-saving measure and to provide experience to frigate captains and officers which would be useful in wartime.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates could also carry marines for boarding enemy ships or for operations on shore; in 1832, the frigate USS *Potomac* landed a party of 282 sailors and Marines ashore in the US Navy's first Sumatran expedition.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates remained a crucial element of navies until the mid-19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The first ironclads were classified as "frigates" because of the number of guns they carried.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] However, terminology changed as iron and steam became the norm, and the role of the frigate was assumed first by the protected cruiser and then by the light cruiser.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates are often the vessel of choice in historical naval novels due to their relative freedom compared to ships-of-the-line (kept for fleet actions) and smaller vessels (generally assigned to a home port and less widely ranging).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] For example, the Patrick O'Brian Aubrey–Maturin series, C.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Forester's Horatio Hornblower series and Alexander Kent's Richard Bolitho series.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The 2003 film *Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World* features a reconstructed historic frigate, HMS *Rose*, to depict Aubrey's frigate HMS *Surprise*.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Vessels classed as frigates continued to play a great role in navies with the adoption of steam power in the 19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 1830s, navies experimented with large paddle steamers equipped with large guns mounted on one deck, which were termed "paddle frigates".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] From the mid-1840s on, frigates which more closely resembled the traditional sailing frigate were built with steam engines and screw propellers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] These "screw frigates", built first of wood and later of iron, continued to perform the traditional role of the frigate until late in the 19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] From 1859, armour was added to ships based on existing frigate and ship of the line designs.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The additional weight of the armour on these first ironclad warships meant that they could have only one gun deck, and they were technically frigates, even though they were more powerful than existing ships-of-the-line and occupied the same strategic role.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The phrase "armoured frigate" remained in use for some time to denote a sail-equipped, broadside-firing type of ironclad.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The first such ship was the revolutionary Marine Nationale wooden-hulled *Gloire*, protected by 12 cm-thick (4.7 in) armour plates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The British response was HMS *Warrior* of the Warrior-class ironclads, launched in 1860.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] With her iron hull, steam engines propelling the 9,137 ton vessel to speeds of up to 14 knots and rifled breechloading 110-pdr guns, *Warrior* is the ancestor of all modern warships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] During the 1880s, as warship design shifted from iron to steel and cruising warships without sails started to appear, the term "frigate" fell out of use.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Vessels with armoured sides were designated as "battleships" or "armoured cruisers", while "protected cruisers" only possessed an armoured deck, and unarmoured vessels, including frigates and sloops, were classified as "unprotected cruisers".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Modern frigates are related to earlier frigates only by name.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The term "frigate" was readopted during the Second World War by the British Royal Navy to describe an anti-submarine escort vessel that was larger than a corvette (based on a mercantile design), while smaller than a destroyer.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The vessels were originally to be termed "twin screw corvettes" until the Royal Canadian Navy suggested to the British re-introducing the term "frigate" for the significantly enlarged vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates, termed destroyer escorts by the US at the time, are less expensive to build and maintain than larger destroyers and cruisers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] 22 of these were reclassified as frigates after the war, as were the remaining 24 smaller Castle-class corvettes.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate was introduced to remedy some of the shortcomings inherent in the Flower-class corvette design: limited armament, a hull form not suited to open-ocean work, a single shaft which limited speed and manoeuvrability, and a lack of range.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate was designed and built to the same mercantile construction standards (scantlings) as the corvette, allowing manufacture by yards unused to warship construction.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The first frigates of the River class (1941) were essentially two sets of corvette machinery in one larger hull, armed with the latest Hedgehog anti-submarine weapon.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate possessed less offensive firepower and speed than a destroyer, including an escort destroyer, but such qualities were not required for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Submarines were slow while submerged, and ASDIC sets did not operate effectively at speeds of over 20 knots (23 mph; 37 km/h).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Rather, the frigate was an austere and weatherly vessel suitable for mass-construction and fitted with the latest innovations in anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] As the frigate was intended purely for convoy duties, and not to deploy with the fleet, it had limited range and speed.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] It was not until the Royal Navy's Bay class of 1944 that a British design classified as a "frigate" was produced for fleet use, although it still suffered from limited speed.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] These anti-aircraft frigates, built on incomplete Loch-class frigate hulls, were similar to the United States Navy's destroyer escorts (DE), although the latter had greater speed and offensive armament to better suit them to fleet deployments.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The destroyer escort concept came from design studies by the General Board of the United States Navy in 1940, as modified by requirements established by a British commission in 1941 prior to the American entry into the war, for deep-water escorts.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The American-built destroyer escorts serving in the Royal Navy were rated as Captain-class frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Navy's two Canadian-built *Asheville*-class and 96 British-influenced, American-built *Tacoma*-class frigates that followed originally were classified as "patrol gunboats" (PG) in the U.S.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Navy but on 15 April 1943 were all reclassified as **patrol frigates (PF)**.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The introduction of the surface-to-air missile after World War II made relatively small ships effective for anti-aircraft warfare: the "guided-missile frigate".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In the US navy, these vessels were called "ocean escorts" and designated "DE" or "DEG" until 1975 – a holdover from the World War II destroyer escort or "DE".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] While the Royal Navy used similar designations for their warships built in the 1950s, they maintained the use of the term "frigate"; in the 1990s the RCN re-introduced the frigate designation.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Likewise, the French Navy refers to missile-equipped ships, up to cruiser-sized ships (*Suffren*, *Tourville*, and Horizon classes), by the name of "frégate", while smaller units are named *aviso*.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The Soviet Navy used the term "guard-ship" (*сторожевой корабль*).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] From the 1950s to the 1970s, the United States Navy commissioned ships classed as guided-missile frigates (hull classification symbol DLG or DLGN, literally meaning guided-missile destroyer leaders), which were actually anti-aircraft warfare cruisers built on destroyer-style hulls.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] These had one or two twin launchers per ship for the RIM-2 Terrier missile, upgraded to the RIM-67 Standard ER missile in the 1980s.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] This type of ship was intended primarily to defend aircraft carriers against anti-ship cruise missiles, augmenting and eventually replacing converted World War II cruisers (CAG/CLG/CG) in this role.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The guided-missile frigates also had an anti-submarine capability that most of the World War II cruiser conversions lacked.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Some of these ships – *Bainbridge* and *Truxtun* along with the *California* and *Virginia* classes – were nuclear-powered (DLGN).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] These "frigates" were roughly mid-way in size between cruisers and destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] This was similar to the use of the term "frigate" during the age of sail during which it referred to a medium-sized warship, but it was inconsistent with conventions used by other contemporary navies which regarded frigates as being smaller than destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In the late 1970s, as a gradual successor to the *Knox* frigates, the US Navy introduced the 51-ship *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class guided-missile frigates (FFG), the last of which was decommissioned in 2015, although some serve in other navies.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] By 1995 the older guided-missile cruisers and destroyers were replaced by the *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers and *Arleigh Burke*-class destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] One of the most successful post-1945 designs was the British *Leander*-class frigate, which was used by several navies.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Laid down in 1959, the *Leander* class was based on the previous Type 12 anti-submarine frigate but equipped for anti-aircraft use as well.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] They were used by the UK into the 1990s, at which point some were sold on to other navies.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The *Leander* design, or improved versions of it, were licence-built for other navies as well.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Nearly all modern frigates are equipped with some form of offensive or defensive missiles, and as such are rated as guided-missile frigates (FFG).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Improvements in surface-to-air missiles (e.g., the Eurosam Aster 15) allow modern guided-missile frigates to form the core of many modern navies and to be used as a fleet defence platform, without the need for specialised anti-air warfare frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] They can thus provide theatre wide air and missile defence for forces such as a carrier battle group and typically serve this function".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] By contrast the smaller "frigates are thus usually used as escort vessels to protect sea lines of communication or as an auxiliary component of a strike group".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The largest and most powerful destroyers, such as the *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers, are often classified as cruisers due to their extra armament and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy Type 61 (*Salisbury* class) were "air direction" frigates equipped to track aircraft.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] To this end they had less armament than the Type 41 (*Leopard*-class) air-defence frigates built on the same hull.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Multi-role frigates such as the MEKO 200, *Anzac* and *Halifax* classes are designed for navies needing warships deployed in a variety of situations that a general frigate class would not be able to fulfil, and not requiring destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] At the opposite end of the spectrum, some frigates are specialised for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Increasing submarine speeds towards the end of World War II (see German Type XXI submarine) greatly reduced the margin of speed superiority of frigate over submarine.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate could no longer be slow and powered by mercantile machinery, and consequently postwar frigates such as the *Whitby* class were faster.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Such ships carry improved sonar equipment, such as the variable depth sonar or towed array, and specialised weapons such as torpedoes, forward-throwing weapons such as Limbo and missile-carried anti-submarine torpedoes such as ASROC or Ikara.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy's original Type 22 frigate is an example of a specialised anti-submarine warfare frigate, though it also has Sea Wolf surface-to-air missiles for point defence plus Exocet surface-to-surface missiles for limited offensive capability.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Especially for anti-submarine warfare, most modern frigates have a landing deck and hangar aft to operate helicopters, eliminating the need for the frigate to close with unknown sub-surface threats, and using fast helicopters to attack nuclear submarines which may be faster than surface warships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] For this task the helicopter is equipped with sensors such as sonobuoys, wire-mounted dipping sonar and magnetic anomaly detectors to identify possible threats, and torpedoes or depth-charges to attack them.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] With their onboard radar helicopters can also be used to reconnoitre over-the-horizon targets and, if equipped with anti-ship missiles such as Penguin or Sea Skua, to attack them.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The helicopter is also invaluable for search and rescue operation and has largely replaced the use of small boats or the jackstay rig for such duties as transferring personnel, mail and cargo between ships or to shore.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] With helicopters these tasks can be accomplished faster and less dangerously, and without the need for the frigate to slow down or change course.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates designed in the 1960s and 1970s, such as the US Navy's *Knox*-class frigate, West Germany's *Bremen*-class frigate, and Royal Navy's Type 22 frigate were equipped with a small number of short-ranged surface-to-air missiles (Sea Sparrow or Sea Wolf) for point defence only.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] By contrast newer frigates starting with the *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigate are specialised for "zone-defence" air defence, because of major developments in fighter jets and cruise missiles.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Recent examples include the *De Zeven Provinciën*-class air defence and command frigate of the Royal Netherlands Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Another example is the *Iver Huitfeldt* class of the Royal Danish Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Some new classes of ships similar to corvettes are optimized for high-speed deployment and combat with small craft rather than combat between equal opponents; an example is the U.S. littoral combat ship (LCS).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] As of 2015, all *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigates in the United States Navy have been decommissioned, and their role partially assumed by the new LCS.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] While the LCS class ships are smaller than the frigate class they will replace, they offer a similar degree of weaponry while requiring less than half the crew complement and offering a top speed of over 40 knots (74 km/h; 46 mph).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] A major advantage for the LCS ships is that they are designed around specific mission modules allowing them to fulfil a variety of roles.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The modular system also allows for most upgrades to be performed ashore and installed later into the ship, keeping the ships available for deployment for the maximum time.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The latest U.S. deactivation plans make this the first time that the U.S.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Navy has been without a frigate class of ships since 1943 (technically USS *Constitution* is rated as a frigate and is still in commission, but does not count towards Navy force levels).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The remaining 20 LCSs to be acquired from 2019 and onwards that will be enhanced will be designated as frigates, and existing ships given modifications may also have their classification changed to *FF* as well.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] However, the United States Navy selected a FREMM multipurpose frigate variant for a new *Constellation* class of 20 frigates, to be built by Fincantieri beginning in 2024.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Stealth technology has been introduced in modern frigate design by the French *La Fayette* class design.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigate shapes are designed to offer a minimal radar cross section, which also lends them good air penetration; the manoeuvrability of these frigates has been compared to that of sailing ships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The modern French Navy applies the term first-class frigate and second-class frigate to both destroyers and frigates in service.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Pennant numbers remain divided between F-series numbers for those ships internationally recognised as frigates and D-series pennant numbers for those more traditionally recognised as destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] This can result in some confusion as certain classes are referred to as frigates in French service while similar ships in other navies are referred to as destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] This also results in some recent classes of French ships such as the Horizon class being among the largest in the world to carry the rating of frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The *Frégates de Taille Intermédiaire* (FTI), which means frigates of intermediate size, is a French military program to design and create a planned class of frigates to be used by the French Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] At the moment, the program consists of five ships, with commissioning planned from 2023.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] In the German Navy, frigates were used to replace ageing destroyers; however in size and role the new German frigates exceed the former class of destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The current German F125 Baden-Württemberg-class frigates are the largest class of frigates worldwide with a displacement of more than 7,200 tons .
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The same was done in the Spanish Navy, which went ahead with the deployment of the first Aegis frigates, the *Álvaro de Bazán*-class frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The Myanmar Navy is producing modern frigates with a reduced radar cross section known as the Kyan Sittha-class frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Before the Kyan Sittha class, the Myanmar Navy also produced an *Aung Zeya*-class frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] Although the size of the Myanmar Navy is quite small, it is producing modern guided-missile frigates with the help of Russia, China, and India.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] However, the fleets of the Myanmar Navy are still expanding with several on-going shipbuilding programmes, including one 135 m (442 ft 11 in), 4,000-tonne frigate with the vertical missile launch systems.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] The four planned *Tamandaré*-class frigates of the Brazilian Navy will be responsible for introducing ships with stealth technology in the national navy and the Latin American region, with the first boat expected to be launched in 2024.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] A few frigates have survived as museum ships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/armoured-frigate-p01] These ships are classified by their respective nations as frigates, but are considered destroyers internationally due to size, armament, and role.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The **military port of Toulon** (French: *arsenal de Toulon*) is the principal base of the French Navy and the largest naval base in the Mediterranean and Western Europe, situated in the city of Toulon.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] It holds most of France's force d'action navale, comprising the aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* as well as its nuclear attack submarines, in total, the base contains more than 60% of the French Navy's tonnage, and about 20,000 military and civilian personnel work at the base.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The word *rade* comes from the old English term 'Road,' "a protected place near shore, not so enclosed as a harbour, where ships can ride at anchor.".
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The Rade of Toulon is one of the best natural anchorages on the Mediterranean, and the largest rade in Europe.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] It is protected from the sea by the peninsula of Giens and the peninsula of Saint-Mandrier-sur-Mer, and has been used as a military harbour since the 15th century.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The Rade shelters the port of Saint-Mandrier-sur-Mer, the port of La Seyne-sur-Mer, as well as the arsenal, or military port of Toulon, and the commercial port.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The 'modern' history of the port began when Louis XII built his Tour Royale at Toulon in 1514.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] A naval arsenal and shipyard were built in 1599, and small sheltered harbour, the Veille Darse, was built in 1604–1610 to protect ships from the wind and sea.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The shipyard was greatly enlarged by Cardinal Richelieu, who wished to make France into a Mediterranean naval power.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] In 1680, Jean-Baptiste Colbert, Secretary of State of the Navy and Controller of Finance of King Louis XIV, began building a much larger port, called the Darse Vauban or the Darse Neuve, and shipyard, designed by his commissioner of fortifications, Vauban.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] In 1697, Vauban built the impressive corderie, a building designed to make ropes.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The corderie, still standing, is 20 metres wide and 320 metres long, built so that ropes could be stretched the entire length of the building as they were twisted together.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] Power for the ropemaking was provided by convicts from the adjoining prison, the Bagne de Toulon, who walked in an enormous treadmill.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] A triumphal gate (now the Museum of the Navy) was added to the Arsenal in 1738.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The Arsenal port was enlarged still further in the 19th century and the 20th century.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The construction of the arsenal du Mourillon began at the start of the 18th century, as an extension of the major Toulon arsenal on the roadstead's east coast.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] Until the 20th century this extension held stores for the wood to build the French Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] From the late 19th century it was this shipyard that built France's first ironclad frigates then the world's first modern submarines.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] Rather than joining the Free French forces in North Africa and to avoid capture by the Germans, the French fleet based at Toulon scuttled itself on 27 November 1942 on the orders of the French admiralty.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] During the 20th century the Mourillon arsenal was mainly dedicated to submarine activity as a French submarine base until 1940, then a German one from 1940 to 1945, then a dockyard and torpedo factory after 1945.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The Arsenal was badly damaged by Allied bombing in World War II, but since has been reconstructed and modernised.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] It has eleven drydocks for ship repair, the two largest of which are 422 metres by 40 metres.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The Arsenal is still the principal military port of France, the home port of the aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle,* France's attack submarine squadron, and the other ships of the French Mediterranean fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The Arsenal is not open to the public, but the Naval Museum at its entrance has a collection of enormous ship models from the 18th century, used to train the heir to the throne in seamanship, as well as other naval memorabilia.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The building of the Corderie can be seen beside the road nearby.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] Boat tours depart regularly from the waterfront, and allow visitors to have a good look at ships of the French fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The military base is divided into four main zones, each with their own access to the sea.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The three other gates are secondary and little used, though still heavily guarded.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] To the extreme west in the communes of La Seyne-sur-Mer and Ollioules the military base is in contact with the commercial port of Brégaillon, connected to national and regional networks for the supply of artillery munitions and other supplies.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The arsenal du Mourillon, next to the roadstead, is directly accessible via the north arsenal which housed a submarine base until 1945.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The south arsenal is accessed by the small slipway of Le Mourillon beside the now-disappeared torpedo factory.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The military bases possesses more than 30 km of roads, railway level crossings, traffic lights, signs, etc..
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] It also has an SNCF rail line running from the station at La Seyne-sur-Mer to the docks via its storage sheds.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] Used to harbour foreign ships, or large ships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] Traditionally, this quay was used to honour distinguished ships by putting them into view from the merchant harbour.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The four dry docks are fit for repairs on medium to large craft.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The Vaudan dock is used as a mooring for small ships (diver support, mine warfare, tugs, patrol boats) and elder ships.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The quays are fitted with mobile roofs that cover the submarines when their nuclear equipment is being refitted.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] These quays also comprise a number of dry docks.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/arsenal-de-toulon] The main mooring stations of the harbour, where frigates, aircraft carriers, fleet tankers and landing ships are stationed.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/barquentine] A **barquentine** or **schooner barque** (alternatively "barkentine" or "schooner bark") is a sailing vessel with three or more masts, with a square rigged foremast and fore-and-aft rigged main, mizzen and any other masts.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/barquentine] While a full-rigged ship is square-rigged on all three masts, and the barque is square-rigged except for the mizzen-mast, the barquentine extends the principle by making only the foremast square-rigged.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/barquentine] The advantages of a smaller crew, good performance before the wind and the ability to sail relatively close to the wind while carrying plenty of cargo made it a popular rig at the end of the nineteenth century.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/barquentine] Today, barquentines are popular with modern tall ship and sail training operators as their suite of mainly fore-and-aft sails improve non-downwind performance, while their foremast of square sails offers long distance downwind speed and dramatic appearance in port.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/barquentine] The term "barquentine" is seventeenth-century in origin, formed from "barque" in imitation of "brigantine", a two-masted vessel square-rigged only on the forward mast, and apparently formed from the word brig.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] The **beam** of a ship is its width at its widest point.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] The **maximum beam** (BMAX) is the distance between planes passing through the outer sides of the ship, **beam of the hull** (BH) only includes permanently fixed parts of the hull, and **beam at waterline** (BWL) is the maximum width where the hull intersects the surface of the water.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] Generally speaking, the wider the beam of a ship (or boat), the more initial stability it has, at the expense of secondary stability in the event of a capsize, where more energy is required to right the vessel from its inverted position.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] A ship that heels on her *beam ends* has her deck beams nearly vertical.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] Typical length-to-beam ratios (aspect ratios) for small sailboats are from 2:1 (dinghies to trailerable sailboats around 20 ft or 6 m) to 5:1 (racing sailboats over 30 ft or 10 m).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] Large ships have widely varying beam ratios, some as large as 20:1.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] Rowing shells designed for flatwater racing may have length to beam ratios as high as 30:1, while a coracle has a ratio of almost 1:1 – it is nearly circular.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] Where LOA is Length OverAll and all lengths are in feet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] As catamarans have more than one hull, there is a different beam calculation for this kind of vessel.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] This term in typically used in conjunction with LOA (Length overall).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] The ratio of LOA/BOC is used to estimate the stability of multihull vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] The lower the ratio the greater the boat's stability.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/beam-nautical] The BOC for vessels is measured as follows: For a catamaran: the perpendicular distance from the centerline of one hull to the centerline of the other hull, measured at deck level.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] A **blockade** is the use of military force to prevent food, supplies, weapons, or communications, and sometimes people, entering or leaving a country or region.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Unlike sanctions or an embargo, which are legal barriers to trade, a blockade is physical.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Blockades are distinct from sieges in that a blockade is usually directed at an entire country or region, rather than a fortress or city, and the objective of a blockade is not necessarily to conquer the area.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] A blockading power can seek to cut off all maritime transport from and to the blockaded country, although stopping all land transport to and from an area may also be considered a blockade.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Blockades restrict the trading rights of neutral parties, who must submit for inspection for contraband, which the blockading power may define narrowly or broadly, sometimes including food and medicine.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] In the 20th century, air power has also been used to enhance the effectiveness of blockades by halting air traffic within the blockaded airspace.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Close patrol of hostile ports, in order to prevent naval forces from putting to sea, is also referred to as a blockade.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] When coastal cities or fortresses were besieged from the landward side, the besiegers would often blockade the seaward side as well.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Modern blockades have included cutting off electronic communications by jamming radio signals and severing undersea cables.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Blockades often result in the starvation of the civilian population, notably during the blockade of Germany during World War I and the blockade of Biafra during the Nigerian Civil War.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Although primitive naval blockades have been in use for millennia, early attempts were limited by the time ships were able to stay at sea uninterruptedly.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The first successful attempts at establishing a full naval blockade were made by the British Royal Navy during the Seven Years' War (1754–1763) against France.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Following the 1759 British naval victory at Quiberon Bay, which ended any immediate threat of a major invasion of Britain, the British Royal Navy established a close blockade on the French coast.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] This starved French ports of commerce, weakening France's economy.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Admiral Edward Hawke took command of the blockading fleet off Brest and extended the blockade to cover the entire French Atlantic coast from Dunkirk to Bordeaux, and to Marseille on France's Mediterranean coast.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] During the North American operations of the Seven Years' War, the British Royal Navy blockaded the French on the other side of the Atlantic, specifically impeding access and supply to the colonies of New France on the St.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Blockades contributed to the French loss of Canada in 1763.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The strategic importance of blockade became increasingly apparent during the French Revolutionary Wars of 1792 to 1802 and in the Napoleonic Wars of 1803 to 1815, when the Royal Navy successfully blockaded France, leading to major economic disruptions.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The Union blockade of southern ports was a major factor in the American Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] During World War I (1914–1918), the Allies blockaded the Central Powers, depriving them of food-supplies and strategic materials.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Germany's attempted U-boat blockade of Britain caused some shortages, but ultimately failed.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] A similar outcome followed in World War II (1939–1945).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Naval strategic thinkers, such as Sir Julian Corbett (1854–1922) and Alfred Thayer Mahan (1840–1914), wrote that naval conflicts were won primarily by decisive battles, but also by blockade.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] A *close* blockade entails placing warships within sight of the blockaded coast or port, to ensure the immediate interception of any ship entering or leaving.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] It is both the most effective and the most difficult form of blockade to implement.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Difficulties arise because the blockading ships must remain continuously at sea, exposed to storms and hardship, usually far from any support, and vulnerable to sudden attack from the blockaded side, whose ships may stay safe in harbor until they choose to come out.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] In a *distant* blockade, the blockaders stay well away from the blockaded coast and try to intercept any ships going in or out.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] This may require more ships on station, but they can usually operate closer to their bases, and are at much less risk from enemy raids.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] This was almost impossible prior to the 16th century due to the nature of the ships used.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] A *loose* blockade is a close blockade where the blockading ships are withdrawn out of sight from the coast, behind the horizon, but no farther.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The object of loose blockade is to lure the enemy into venturing out but to stay close enough to strike.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] British admiral Horatio Nelson applied a loose blockade at Cádiz in 1805.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The Franco-Spanish fleet under Pierre-Charles Villeneuve then came out, resulting in the Battle of Trafalgar.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Until 1827, blockades, as part of economic warfare, were always a part of a war.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] This changed when France, Russia and Britain came to the aid of the Greek rebels against Turkey.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] They blockaded the Turkish-occupied coast, which led to the battle of Navarino.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] War was never declared, so it is considered the first *pacific* – i.e., peaceful – blockade.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The first truly pacific blockade, involving no shooting at all, was the British blockade of the Republic of New Granada in 1837, established to compel New Granada to release an imprisoned British consul.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Since 1945, the United Nations Security Council determines the legal status of blockades.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] By article 42 of the UN Charter, the council can also apply blockades.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The UN Charter allows for the right of self-defense but requires that this must be immediately reported to the Security Council to ensure the maintenance of international peace.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] According to the not ratified document San Remo Manual on International Law Applicable to Armed Conflicts at Sea, June 1994, a blockade is a legal method of warfare at sea, but is governed by rules.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The manual describes what can never be contraband.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The blockading nation is free to select anything else as contraband in a list, which it must publish.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] The blockading nation typically establishes a blockaded area of water, and any ship can be inspected as soon as it is established that it is attempting to break the blockade.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] This inspection can occur inside the blockaded area or in international waters, but never inside the territorial waters of a neutral nation.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] A neutral ship must obey a request to stop for inspection from the blockading nation.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] If the situation so demands, the blockading nation can request that the ship divert to a known place or harbour for inspection.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] If the ship does not stop, then the ship is subject to capture.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] If people aboard the ship resist capture, they can be lawfully attacked.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] According to modern international law, blockades are an act of war.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] A blockade is therefore only legal if applied in self-defense, and not as part of a war of aggression.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Blockades are illegal when used as to starve or to collectively punish a civilian population.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Such a blockade is a war crime and potentially a crime against humanity.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Blockade running is the practice of delivering cargo, food, for example, to a blockaded area.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] It has mainly been done by ships called blockade runners to ports under naval blockade.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] Blockade runners were typically the fastest ships available and often lightly armed and armored.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/blockade] It is now also done by aircraft, forming airbridges, such as over the Berlin Blockade after World War II.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] A **boiler** is a closed vessel in which fluid (generally water) is heated.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The heated or vaporized fluid exits the boiler for use in various processes or heating applications, including water heating, central heating, boiler-based power generation, cooking, and sanitation.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] In a fossil fuel power plant using a steam cycle for power generation, the primary heat source will be combustion of coal, oil, or natural gas.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] In some cases byproduct fuel such as the carbon monoxide rich offgasses of a coke battery can be burned to heat a boiler; biofuels such as bagasse, where economically available, can also be used.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] In a nuclear power plant, boilers called steam generators are heated by the heat produced by nuclear fission.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Where a large volume of hot gas is available from some process, a heat recovery steam generator or recovery boiler can use the heat to produce steam, with little or no extra fuel consumed; such a configuration is common in a combined cycle power plant where a gas turbine and a steam boiler are used.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] In all cases the combustion product waste gases are separate from the working fluid of the steam cycle, making these systems examples of external combustion engines.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The pressure vessel of a boiler is usually made of steel (or alloy steel), or historically of wrought iron.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Stainless steel, especially of the austenitic types, is not used in wetted parts of boilers due to corrosion and stress corrosion cracking.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] However, ferritic stainless steel is often used in superheater sections that will not be exposed to boiling water, and electrically heated stainless steel shell boilers are allowed under the European "Pressure Equipment Directive" for production of steam for sterilizers and disinfectors.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] In live steam models, copper or brass is often used because it is more easily fabricated in smaller size boilers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] For much of the Victorian "age of steam", the only material used for boilermaking was the highest grade of wrought iron, with assembly by riveting.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] This iron was often obtained from specialist ironworks, such as those in the Cleator Moor (UK) area, noted for the high quality of their rolled plate, which was especially suitable for use in critical applications such as high-pressure boilers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] In the 20th century, design practice moved towards the use of steel, with welded construction, which is stronger and cheaper, and can be fabricated more quickly and with less labour.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Wrought iron boilers corrode far more slowly than their modern-day steel counterparts, and are less susceptible to localized pitting and stress-corrosion.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] That makes the longevity of older wrought-iron boilers far superior to that of welded steel boilers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Cast iron may be used for the heating vessel of domestic water heaters.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Although such heaters are usually termed "boilers" in some countries, their purpose is usually to produce hot water, not steam, and so they run at low pressure and try to avoid boiling.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The brittleness of cast iron makes it impractical for high-pressure steam boilers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The source of heat for a boiler is combustion of any of several fuels, such as wood, coal, oil, or natural gas.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Electric steam boilers use resistance- or immersion-type heating elements.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Nuclear fission is also used as a heat source for generating steam, either directly (BWR) or, in most cases, in specialised heat exchangers called "steam generators" (PWR).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Heat recovery steam generators (HRSGs) use the heat rejected from other processes such as gas turbine.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Direct method of boiler efficiency test is more usable or more common.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] A primitive "kettle" where a fire heats a partially filled water container from below.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] 18th-century Haycock boilers generally produced and stored large volumes of very low-pressure steam, often hardly above that of the atmosphere.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] These could burn wood or most often, coal.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] This is the type of boiler used in nearly all steam locomotives.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Fire-tube boilers usually have a comparatively low rate of steam production, but high steam storage capacity.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Fire-tube boilers mostly burn solid fuels, but are readily adaptable to those of the liquid or gas variety.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Fire-tube boilers may also be referred to as "scotch-marine" or "marine" type boilers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] In this type, tubes filled with water are arranged inside a furnace in a number of possible configurations.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Often the water tubes connect large drums, the lower ones containing water and the upper ones steam and water; in other cases, such as a mono-tube boiler, water is circulated by a pump through a succession of coils.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] This type generally gives high steam production rates, but less storage capacity than fire-tube boilers.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Water tube boilers can be designed to exploit any heat source and are generally preferred in high-pressure applications since the high-pressure water/steam is contained within small diameter pipes which can withstand the pressure with a thinner wall.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] These boilers are commonly constructed in place, roughly square in shape, and can be multiple stories tall.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] A flash boiler is a specialized type of water-tube boiler in which tubes are close together and water is pumped through them.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] A flash boiler differs from the type of mono-tube steam generator in which the tube is permanently filled with water.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Flash boilers had some use in automobiles in the 19th century and this use continued into the early 20th century.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The gases then pass through a conventional firetube boiler.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] but have met with little success in other countries.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] In a cast iron sectional boiler, sometimes called a "pork chop boiler" the water is contained inside cast iron sections.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] These sections are assembled on site to create the finished boiler.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] To define and secure boilers safely, some professional specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] For instance, the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code is a standard providing a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the boilers and other pressure vessels with safety, security and design standards.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Historically, boilers were a source of many serious injuries and property destruction due to poorly understood engineering principles.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Thin and brittle metal shells can rupture, while poorly welded or riveted seams could open up, leading to a violent eruption of the pressurized steam.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] When water is converted to steam it expands to over 1,000 times its original volume and travels down steam pipes at over 100 kilometres per hour (62 mph).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Because of this, steam is an efficient method of moving energy and heat around a site from a central boiler house to where it is needed, but without the right boiler feedwater treatment, a steam-raising plant will suffer from scale formation and corrosion.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] At best, this increases energy costs and can lead to poor quality steam, reduced efficiency, shorter plant life and unreliable operation.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] At worst, it can lead to catastrophic failure and loss of life.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Collapsed or dislodged boiler tubes can also spray scalding-hot steam and smoke out of the air intake and firing chute, injuring the firemen who load the coal into the fire chamber.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Extremely large boilers providing hundreds of horsepower to operate factories can potentially demolish entire buildings.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] A boiler that has a loss of feed water and is permitted to boil dry can be extremely dangerous.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] If feed water is then sent into the empty boiler, the small cascade of incoming water instantly boils on contact with the superheated metal shell and leads to a violent explosion that cannot be controlled even by safety steam valves.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Draining of the boiler can also happen if a leak occurs in the steam supply lines that is larger than the make-up water supply could replace.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The *Hartford Loop* was invented in 1919 by the Hartford Steam Boiler Inspection and Insurance Company as a method to help prevent this condition from occurring, and thereby reduce their insurance claims.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] When water is boiled the result is saturated steam, also referred to as "wet steam." Saturated steam, while mostly consisting of water vapor, carries some unevaporated water in the form of droplets.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Saturated steam is useful for many purposes, such as cooking, heating and sanitation, but is not desirable when steam is expected to convey energy to machinery, such as a ship's propulsion system or the "motion" of a steam locomotive.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] This is because unavoidable temperature and/or pressure loss that occurs as steam travels from the boiler to the machinery will cause some condensation, resulting in liquid water being carried into the machinery.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The water entrained in the steam may damage turbine blades or in the case of a reciprocating steam engine, may cause serious mechanical damage due to hydrostatic lock.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Superheated steam boilers evaporate the water and then further heat the steam in a *superheater*, causing the discharged steam temperature to be substantially above the boiling temperature at the boiler's operating pressure.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] As the resulting "dry steam" is much hotter than needed to stay in the vaporous state it will not contain any significant unevaporated water.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Also, higher steam pressure will be possible than with saturated steam, enabling the steam to carry more energy.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Although superheating adds more energy to the steam in the form of heat there is no effect on pressure, which is determined by the rate at which steam is drawn from the boiler and the pressure settings of the safety valves.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The fuel consumption required to generate superheated steam is greater than that required to generate an equivalent volume of saturated steam.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] However, the overall energy efficiency of the steam plant (the combination of boiler, superheater, piping and machinery) generally will be improved enough to more than offset the increased fuel consumption.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Superheater operation is similar to that of the coils on an air conditioning unit, although for a different purpose.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The steam piping is directed through the flue gas path in the boiler furnace, an area in which the temperature is typically between 1,300 and 1,600 degrees Celsius (2,372 and 2,912 degrees Fahrenheit).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Some superheaters are radiant type, which as the name suggests, they absorb heat by radiation.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Others are convection type, absorbing heat from a fluid.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Some are a combination of the two types.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Through either method, the extreme heat in the flue gas path will also heat the superheater steam piping and the steam within.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The design of any superheated steam plant presents several engineering challenges due to the high working temperatures and pressures.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] One consideration is the introduction of feedwater to the boiler.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The pump used to charge the boiler must be able to overcome the boiler's operating pressure, else water will not flow.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] As a superheated boiler is usually operated at high pressure, the corresponding feedwater pressure must be even higher, demanding a more robust pump design.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] High pressure, superheated steam can be extremely dangerous if it unintentionally escapes.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] To give the reader some perspective, the steam plants used in many U.S.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Navy destroyers built during World War II operated at 600 psi (4,100 kPa; 41 bar) pressure and 850 degrees Fahrenheit (454 degrees Celsius) superheat.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Also, small leaks that are not visible at the point of leakage could be lethal if an individual were to step into the escaping steam's path.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Hence designers endeavor to give the steam-handling components of the system as much strength as possible to maintain integrity.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Special methods of coupling steam pipes together are used to prevent leaks, with very high pressure systems employing welded joints to avoid leakage problems with threaded or gasketed connections.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Supercritical steam generators are frequently used for the production of electric power.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] In contrast to a "subcritical boiler", a supercritical steam generator operates at such a high pressure (over 3,200 psi or 22 MPa) that the physical turbulence that characterizes boiling ceases to occur; the fluid is neither liquid nor gas but a supercritical fluid.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] There is no generation of steam bubbles within the water, because the pressure is above the critical pressure point at which steam bubbles can form.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] As the fluid expands through the turbine stages, its thermodynamic state drops below the critical point as it does work turning the turbine which turns the electrical generator from which power is ultimately extracted.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The fluid at that point may be a mix of steam and liquid droplets as it passes into the condenser.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] This results in slightly less fuel use and therefore less greenhouse gas production.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The term "boiler" should not be used for a supercritical pressure steam generator, as no "boiling" occurs in this device.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] A fuel-heated boiler must provide air to oxidize its fuel.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Early boilers provided this stream of air, or *draught*, through the natural action of convection in a chimney connected to the exhaust of the combustion chamber.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Since the heated flue gas is less dense than the ambient air surrounding the boiler, the flue gas rises in the chimney, pulling denser, fresh air into the combustion chamber.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Most modern boilers depend on mechanical draught rather than natural draught.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] This is because natural draught is subject to outside air conditions and temperature of flue gases leaving the furnace, as well as the chimney height.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] All these factors make proper draught hard to attain and therefore make mechanical draught equipment much more reliable and economical.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Types of draught can also be divided into *induced draught*, where exhaust gases are pulled out of the boiler; *forced draught*, where fresh air is pushed into the boiler; and *balanced draught*, where both effects are employed.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Natural draught through the use of a chimney is a type of induced draught; mechanical draught can be induced, forced or balanced.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] There are two types of mechanical induced draught.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The first is through use of a steam jet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The steam jet oriented in the direction of flue gas flow induces flue gases into the stack and allows for a greater flue gas velocity increasing the overall draught in the furnace.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] This method was common on steam driven locomotives which could not have tall chimneys.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The second method is by simply using an induced draught fan (ID fan) which removes flue gases from the furnace and forces the exhaust gas up the stack.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Almost all induced draught furnaces operate with a slightly negative pressure.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Mechanical forced draught is provided by means of a fan forcing air into the combustion chamber.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Air is often passed through an air heater; which, as the name suggests, heats the air going into the furnace to increase the overall efficiency of the boiler.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Dampers are used to control the quantity of air admitted to the furnace.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Forced draught furnaces usually have a positive pressure.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] Balanced draught is obtained through use of both induced and forced draught.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] This is more common with larger boilers where the flue gases have to travel a long distance through many boiler passes.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/boiler-steam-generator] The induced draught fan works in conjunction with the forced draught fan allowing the furnace pressure to be maintained slightly below atmospheric.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] The **French ironclad *Invincible*** was the second of the three wooden-hulled *Gloire*-class ironclads built for the French Navy in 1858–1862.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] The ships of the *Gloire* class were classified as armoured frigates because they only had a single gun deck and their traditional disposition of guns arrayed along the length of the hull also meant that they were broadside ironclads.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] *Invincible* had an uneventful career and was deployed in North American waters during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] The unseasoned timber of her hull rotted quickly and she was condemned in 1872 and scrapped in 1876.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] Designed by the French naval architect Henri Dupuy de Lôme, the ships of the class were intended to fight in the line of battle, unlike the first British ironclads.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] The ship was 77.25 metres (253 ft 5 in) long, with a beam of 17 metres (55 ft 9 in).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] *Invincible* had a maximum draft of 8.48 metres (27 ft 10 in), a depth of hold of 10.67 metres (35 ft 0 in) and displaced 5,650 tonnes (5,560 long tons).
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] The ships of the class had a high metacentric height of 2.1 metres (7 ft) and consequently rolled badly.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] With their gun ports only 1.88 metres (6 ft 2 in) above the waterline, they proved to be very wet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] She had a crew of 570 officers and enlisted men.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] The *Gloire*-class ships were armed with 36 Modèle 1858 164.7-millimetre (6.5 in) rifled muzzle-loading guns, 34 of which were positioned on the single gun deck in the broadside.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] The remaining two guns were placed on the upper deck as chase guns.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] They fired a 44.9-kilogram (99.0 lb) shell at a muzzle velocity of only 322 metres per second (1,060 ft/s) and proved to be ineffective against armour.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] They were replaced by rifled breech-loading Modèle 1864 guns in 1868.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] Six 240-millimetre (9.4 in) guns were mounted in the centre of the gun deck and a pair of 194-millimetre (7.6 in) guns replaced the original chase guns.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] Ordered on 4 March 1858, *Invincible* was laid down at the Arsenal de Toulon on 1 May 1858, launched on 4 April 1861 and completed in March 1862.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] In September–October 1863, she conducted tactical trials with other ironclads.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] While assigned to the Mediterranean Fleet, the ship made a port visit in August 1865 to Brest where the fleet hosted the British Channel Fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] As part of the festivities, *Invincible* put on a banquet for the midshipmen of both fleets that was reportedly the noisiest and most enjoyable of the visit.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] A few days later the French fleet made a reciprocal visit to Portsmouth where it was hosted by the Channel Fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] During the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71, the ship was sent to defend the islands of Saint Pierre and Miquelon from Prussian commerce raiders.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] Built of unseasoned timber, *Invincible* was in poor shape upon her return and was decommissioned.
[src:french-ironclad-invincible/french-ironclad-invincible] Removed from the naval register on 12 August 1872, the ship was scrapped in 1876 at Cherbourg.
